bayou.jtype

Class ClassType<T>

  • java.lang.Object

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    TypeArg

    public abstract class ClassType<T>
extends ReferenceType<T>
    Class or interface type. ( Ideally this should be named as ClassOrInterfaceType, but that would be too long. )

    A ClassType may represent a parameterized types, e.g. Map<String,Integer>.

    A ClassType can be created by one of the static factory methods, for example 

         ClassType< Map<String,Integer> > type = ClassType.of(Map.class, String.class, Integer.class);

    or as "type literal" by anonymous subclass , for example 

         new ClassType< List<String> > (){}

      • of

        public static <C,T extends C> ClassType<T> of(Class<C> clazz,
                                              Class<?>... typeArgs)
        Create a ClassType with the class and type arguments.

        This is a convenience method for of(Class, TypeArg...) by converting each Class to a TypeArg.

        Example 

             ClassType<Map<String,Integer>> type = ClassType.of(Map.class, String.class, Integer.class);

      • of

        public static <T> ClassType<T> of(Class<T> clazz)
        Create a ClassType representing the class. For example 
             ClassType<String> type = ClassType.of(String.class);

        If `clazz` is generic, this method creates a raw type.

      • withTypeVars

        public static <C> ClassType<? extends C> withTypeVars(Class<C> clazz)
        Create a ClassType, using type variables as type arguments.

        For example, ClassType.withTypeVars(java.util.Map.class) returns a ClassType<K,V> where K,V are type variables defined on java.util.Map<K,V>.

      • getTheClass

        public final Class<T> getTheClass()
        Get the class or interface of this type.

        For example, if this ClassType represents List<String>, this method will return List.class.

        Strictly speaking, the return type of this method should be Class<|T|> where |T| is the erasure of T. However, we cannot express that constraint precisely. Therefore the return type might be for example Class<List<String>> which technically does not exist.

      • getTypeArgs

        public final List<TypeArg> getTypeArgs()
        Get the type arguments.

        For example, if this ClassType represents Map<String,Integer>, this method returns [String,Integer].

        Return an empty list if this is not a parameterized type, either because the class/interface is non-generic, or this is a raw type.

      • getTypeVars

        public final List<TypeVar<?>> getTypeVars()
        Get the type variables of the class/interface definition.

        For example, if getTheClass() is java.util.Map.class, this method returns [K,V] as they are declared on Map.

        Return an empty list if the class/interface is not generic.

      • isRawType

        public final boolean isRawType()
        Whether this is a raw type.

        If the class/interface is generic, but there is no type arguments for this ClassType, this is a raw type.

      • toString

        public final String toString(boolean full)
        Description copied from class: JavaType
        A textual description of the type.

        If `full==false`, simpler names are used for types.

        For example: 

            ClassType< List<String> > type = ClassType.of(List.class, String.class);

    type.toString(true);    //  "java.util.List<java.lang.String>"
    type.toString(false);   //  "List<String>"
